04214nam a22004935i 9780226218830DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20151978ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226218830  a(DE-B1597)524292  a(OCoLC)1055796039  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHV9475 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a365/.9773/251 aJacobs, James B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStateville :bThe Penitentiary in Mass Society /cJames B. Jacobs. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Crime and Justice00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Authoritarian Regime -- tII. The Search for a New Equlllbrium -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStateville penitentiary in Illinois has housed some of Chicago's most infamous criminals and was proclaimed to be "the world's toughest prison" by Joseph Ragen, Stateville's powerful warden from 1936 to 1961. It shares with Attica, San Quentin, and Jackson the notoriety of being one of the maximum security prisons that has shaped the public's conception of imprisonment. In Stateville James B. Jacobs, a sociologist and legal scholar, presents the first historical examination of a total prison organization—administrators, guards, prisoners, and special interest groups. Jacobs applies Edward Shils's interpretation of the dynamics of mass society in order to explain the dramatic events of the past quarter century that have permanently altered Stateville's structure. With the extension of civil rights to previously marginal groups such as racial minorities, the poor, and, ultimately, the incarcerated, prisons have moved from society's periphery toward its center. Accordingly Stateville's control mechanisms became less authoritarian and more legalistic and bureaucratic. As prisoners' rights increased, the preogatives of the staff were sharply curtailed. By the early 1970s the administration proved incapable of dealing with politicized gangs, proliferating interest groups, unionized guards, and interventionist courts. In addition to extensive archival research, Jacobs spent many months freely interacting with the prisoners, guards, and administrators at Stateville. His lucid presentation of Stateville's troubled history will provide fascinating reading for a wide audience of concerned readers. ". . . [an] impressive study of a complex social system."—Isidore Silver, Library Journal  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apenitentiary, society, social studies, illinois, chicago, city, crime, criminals, justice, prison, joseph ragen, warden, 1900s, 1930s, 1940s, 1950s, 1960s, true story, biographical, biography, buildings, maximum security, imprisonment, sociology, sociologist, sociological, legal issues, law, scholarly, academic, research, guards, prisoners, civil rights, race, racism, incarceration, incarcerated, authoritarian, bureaucratic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226218830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226218830/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles